Package io.shiromi.saml.types

Class StringType

java.lang.Object
io.shiromi.saml.types.AbstractType<String>
io.shiromi.saml.types.StringType
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable, Iterable<Character>
public final class StringType extends AbstractType<String> implements Iterable<Character>
Instances of the class StringType carry a value of type String and behave similar to it, as they contain a string as value and allow for easy access via similar methods of String.

However, unlike the class String, this object it iterable and allows for other things String can't do, such as inserting characters or strings at a specific point. As already mentioned, the key difference to String is that this class implements Iterable, therefore marking it as iterable, whereas Strings can only be iterated through by using a normal or enhanced for loop.

Valid arguments this object accepts for constructors are:
  • <no parameter>
  • char
  • char[]
  • String, boolean
  • String
  • StringBuilder
Version:
1.0
Author:
Shiromi

    • StringType

      public StringType(String value, boolean trim)
      Creates a new instance of a StringType with a value and optional trimming of the value, which will remove leading and trailing whitespaces, essentially doing the same as new StringType(" foo ".trim()), which saves using the method trim() and changes not just the AbstractType.value, but also other variables this class has 
      
      StringType st = new StringType("  foo bar  ", true);    // will result in a value of "foo bar"
      st = new StringType("  foo bar  ").trim();              // does the same as above
      Parameters:
      value - the String value of this object
      trim - optional trimming of the string, essentially applying the method trim()

    • split

      public StringType @NotNull [] split(@NotNull @NotNull String delimiter, int limit)
      Splits a string by a given delimiter and returns an array of substrings matched around the given delimiter, the parameter limit specifies the result threshold:
      • If limit is positive, the delimiter will be applied to at most limit - 1, the rest of the string will be added to the last entry of the array
      • if limit is equal to 0, the delimiter will be applied as many time as possible, removing any trailing empty entries
      • if limit is negative, the delimiter will be applied as many times as possible, while leaving any trailing empty spaces
      Parameters:
      delimiter - the delimiter to split by
      limit - the result threshold, as described above
      Returns:
      an array of substrings matched around the delimiter
      See Also:
      • split(char)
      • split(char, int)
      • split(String)

    • split

      public StringType @NotNull [] split(Pattern regex, int limit)
      Splits this object around matches of the given pattern. The array returned by this method contains each substring of this object that is terminated by another subsequence that matches the given pattern, the parameter limit specifies the result threshold:
      • If limit is positive, the delimiter will be applied to at most limit - 1, the rest of the string will be added to the last entry of the array
      • if limit is equal to 0, the delimiter will be applied as many time as possible, removing any trailing empty entries
      • if limit is negative, the delimiter will be applied as many times as possible, while leaving any trailing empty spaces
      Parameters:
      regex - the pattern to split by
      limit - the result threshold, as described above
      Returns:
      an array of substrings matched around the given pattern
      See Also:

    • format

      @NotNull public static @NotNull StringType format(String format, Object... args)
      Format a given input string using these different flags:
      • $s will be replaced with a string representation of the object
      • $d.# will be replaced with a formatted number, see Formatter.numberFormat(double, int)
      • $x/# will be replaced with a formatted hexadecimal string of the object, see Formatter.hexFormat(int, int)
      A few examples: 
      
  StringType.format("foo $s", "bar");   // results in "foo bar"
  StringType.format("Hex: $x/16", 200); // results in "00000000000000C8"
  StringType.format("A few numbers: $d.1, $d.0, $d.5", 5, -15.3, 25.4)
  // results in "A few numbers: 5.0, -15, 25.400000000000000"
      Parameters:
      format - the string to format with the above-mentioned flags
      args - the arguments to format to
      Returns:
      a StringType containing the formatted string, if arguments is not equal to the amount of flags, will return an empty StringType
